metadata.title: Piper PA-28 Cherokee
aws::graph::propositions: Piper PA-28 Cherokee Original Design History
The Cherokee 150 and Cherokee 160 hp were the original Cherokees.
The Cherokee 150 is designated as PA-28-150.
The Cherokee 160 hp is designated as PA-28-160.
The Cherokee 150 and Cherokee 160 hp started production in 1961.
The model number of Cherokee aircraft typically refers to horsepower.
Piper added the Cherokee 180 in 1962.
The Cherokee 180 is designated as PA-28-180.
The Cherokee 180 is powered by a 180 hp Lycoming O-360 engine.
The Lycoming O-360 engine produces 130 kW of power.
The Cherokee 150 produces 110 kW of power.
The Cherokee 160 hp produces 120 kW of power.
The extra power in the Cherokee 180 made it practical to fly with all four seats filled.
The practicality of flying the Cherokee 180 with all seats filled depends on passenger weight and fuel loading.
The Cherokee 180 remains popular on the used-airplane market.
In 1968, the cockpit of the Cherokee was modified.
The modification replaced "push-pull"-style engine throttle controls with quadrant levers.
A third window was added to each side of the fuselage in 1968.
The third window gave the fuselage a more modern look.
The more modern look is seen in most recent production Cherokee aircraft.
Piper continued to expand the Cherokee line rapidly.

text:
### Original design
The original Cherokees were the Cherokee 150 and 160 hp (110 and 120 kW) (PA-28-150 and PA-28-160), which started production in 1961 (unless otherwise mentioned, the model number always refers to horsepower).
In 1962, Piper added the Cherokee 180 (PA-28-180) powered by a 180 hp (130 kW) Lycoming O-360 engine. The extra power made it practical to fly with all four seats filled (depending on passenger weight and fuel loading) and the model remains popular on the used-airplane market. In 1968, the cockpit was modified to replace the "push-pull"-style engine throttle controls with quadrant levers. In addition, a third window was added to each side, giving the fuselage the more modern look seen in most recent production.
Piper continued to expand the line rapidly.
